---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Press + media kit. Asteris Commerce"
  description="Press, founder interview requests, plugin reviews, and media kit assets for Asteris Commerce. Australian WordPress + WooCommerce + Cart plugin company."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Press <span class="accent">+ media kit</span></h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Reviewing one of our plugins for a WordPress publication? Writing about the indie WordPress vendor scene? Looking for the right contact for an interview? Everything you need is below.
      </p>

      <div class="stats">
        <div class="stat"><div class="stat-num">85+</div><div class="stat-label">modules + features<br>across four plugins</div></div>
        <div class="stat"><div class="stat-num">~$3.2k/yr</div><div class="stat-label">replaced by<br>the suite</div></div>
        <div class="stat"><div class="stat-num">2021</div><div class="stat-label">parent company<br>incorporated</div></div>
        <div class="stat"><div class="stat-num">$0</div><div class="stat-label">VC raised<br>(by design)</div></div>
        <div class="stat"><div class="stat-num">Weekly</div><div class="stat-label">ship cadence<br>built in public</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="body">
    <div class="container">

      <h2>Who we are (one-liner)</h2>
      <p class="quote">
        "Asteris Commerce is the plugin-products division of My Cosmic Message Pty Ltd, an Australian WordPress and WooCommerce company incorporated in 2021. The same Pty Ltd operates Orion Web Service (full-stack WP and WC development and hosting since 2021) alongside the Asteris plugin suite (launched 2026). The plugin suite ships three products: Asteris for WordPress (13 modules), Asteris for WooCommerce (20 modules), and Asteris Cart (22 modules). Based in Sydney."
      </p>

      <h2>Who to contact</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>For press inquiries, founder interviews, plugin review copies, partnerships and podcast guesting:</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="mailto:support@asteriscommerce.com">support@asteriscommerce.com</a>. Goes directly to Nick.
      </p>
      <p>
        For product-specific support, use the support address on the relevant product site. The founder inbox is for press, partnerships, and strategic / founder-level inquiries.
      </p>

      <h2>What we'll happily talk about</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Building Asteris from five years of operator pain. Patterns observed running Orion Web Service WC builds for clients since 2021</li>
        <li>Why three focused plugins instead of one mega-plugin</li>
        <li>The Module Quality Protocol. How every module ships against a documented Tier 1+2 gap analysis vs the dominant commercial competitor</li>
        <li>"Built in public, shipping weekly". What that actually means at a small team scale</li>
        <li>Indie WordPress economics in 2026. Self-built Stripe-direct licence platform, no VC, recurring revenue model</li>
        <li>The 2026 plugin-suite-vs-individual-plugins debate (we have opinions)</li>
        <li>Why we built our own checkout funnel plugin instead of buying CartFlows, FunnelKit, or similar competitors</li>
        <li>The relationship between a services business (Orion Web Service) and a products business (Asteris). When it works, what to watch for</li>
        <li>Plugin support economics for small teams. What's automated, what's human, what we'd never automate</li>
        <li>Why we built our own licence and payment infrastructure (pay.asteriscommerce.com) instead of using Freemius, EDD, or Lemon Squeezy</li>
        <li>Australian software business and the AU SaaS ecosystem</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What we'd rather not pitch on</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"AI everything". We use AI where it earns a place (alt text, content briefs, schema gen) and not where it doesn't (the AI Suite module is one of 53 modules, not the headline)</li>
        <li>VC-style growth narratives. We're not raising, and we're not exit-shopping</li>
        <li>Comparisons positioning Asteris as "anti-WooCommerce.com" or "anti-Automattic". We ship plugins for the ecosystem, not against it</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Founder bio</h2>
      <p>
        Nick Lord is the founder and sole director of My Cosmic Message Pty Ltd (incorporated 2021), the Australian company behind both Orion Web Service (a full-stack WordPress and WooCommerce development and hosting business he's run since 2021) and Asteris Commerce (the plugin-products division launched in 2026). Based in Sydney, Australia.
      </p>
      <p>
        Asteris was built from five years of running real WC stores for real clients via Orion Web Service. The 20-module WC plugin, the 11-module WP plugin, and the 22-module Cart plugin cover the categories Nick and his team were buying, integrating, supporting, and updating across dozens of client sites for half a decade. Asteris for WooCommerce v1.0 covers the WC stack. Asteris for WordPress v1.0 covers the same problem for non-commerce WordPress sites. Asteris Cart is the focused checkout, upsell, and cart-recovery product, replacing CartFlows, FunnelKit, and the related funnel stack at a fraction of the combined cost and complexity.
      </p>
      <p>
        Quotable: <em>"I'd rather ship the plugin I wanted as a customer, and as a developer building for clients every day for five years, than the plugin a VC pitch deck wanted me to build."</em>
      </p>

      <h2>Company timeline</h2>
      <ul class="timeline">
        <li>2021. My Cosmic Message Pty Ltd incorporated in NSW, Australia. Orion Web Service launches as a full-stack WordPress and WooCommerce development and hosting business serving Australian and international clients.</li>
        <li>2021 to 2025. Orion Web Service builds and maintains dozens of WC stores. Pattern observed across nearly every client: the same 15 to 25 commercial plugins purchased separately to cover SEO, marketing, payments, performance, security, checkout, funnels. The seed of Asteris.</li>
        <li>2026 (Q1). Asteris Commerce trading name registered. Plugin-products division formally launched within My Cosmic Message Pty Ltd. Module Quality Protocol drafted from five years of client-stack observations.</li>
        <li>2026 (Q2). v1.0 of Asteris for WooCommerce locked at 20 modules. Module Quality Protocol locked as a standing rule (every module ships Tier 1 + Tier 2 gap-analysis-verified vs the dominant commercial competitor before the next module starts).</li>
        <li>2026 (Q2). Asteris for WordPress v1.0 launched. 13 modules covering security, SEO and AI, backups and migration, SMTP and email logs, performance, image optimisation, accessibility, forms, activity log and site health, code snippets, branded links, and first-party insights.</li>
        <li>2026 (Q2). Asteris Cart v1.0 in active build. 22 modules covering checkout, order bumps, upsells, cart recovery, side cart, trust badges, and the funnel-stack categories CartFlows and FunnelKit charge separately for.</li>
        <li>2026 (Q2). Self-built licence and payment platform launched at <code>pay.asteriscommerce.com</code>, replacing the originally-planned Lemon Squeezy merchant-of-record model with Stripe-direct and Cloudflare R2 distribution.</li>
        <li>2026 (Q2). Public launch of Asteris for WooCommerce. Founder cohort opens (100 paid plus 20 competition winners per product). Asteris Free (six modules) submitted to the WordPress.org plugin directory.</li>
        <li>2026 (Q3+). Asteris for WordPress and Asteris Cart v1.0 public launches. Modules 21+ on the WC side enter sprint queue per locked Module Quality Protocol research order.</li>
        <li>Ongoing. Weekly ship cadence across all three products. Public changelog and public roadmap. Founder cohort shapes which modules get prioritised next.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Quick facts</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Parent company incorporated:</strong> 2021 (My Cosmic Message Pty Ltd)</li>
        <li><strong>Asteris Commerce (plugin-products division) launched:</strong> 2026</li>
        <li><strong>Sister business:</strong> Orion Web Service (full-stack WP + WC development + hosting, operating since 2021)</li>
        <li><strong>Legal entity:</strong> My Cosmic Message Pty Ltd t/a Asteris Commerce + t/a Orion Web Service</li>
        <li><strong>ACN / ABN:</strong> 652 358 159 / 30 652 358 159</li>
        <li><strong>Sole director:</strong> Nick Lord</li>
        <li><strong>HQ:</strong> Sydney, NSW, Australia</li>
        <li><strong>Asteris products at launch:</strong> 3. Asteris for WordPress (13 modules), Asteris for WooCommerce (20 modules), Asteris Cart (22 modules)</li>
        <li><strong>Modules total:</strong> 55 paid-tier modules across the three products + 6 modules in Asteris Free (WP.org)</li>
        <li><strong>Distribution:</strong> Direct via product sites + WordPress.org Free editions</li>
        <li><strong>Payments and licence platform:</strong> Self-built on <code>pay.asteriscommerce.com</code>. Stripe direct, Cloudflare R2 distribution, no third-party merchant of record</li>
        <li><strong>Funding:</strong> Bootstrapped from Orion Web Service revenue + launch-locked Founder subscriptions + standing subscriptions thereafter. No VC, no angels.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Press releases</h2>
      <p>
        We'll archive every formal press release here once they start landing. For now this section is intentionally empty. Asteris hasn't issued any formal releases yet (launch is the first). If you're after a comment or quote on a specific story before that, email <a href="mailto:support@asteriscommerce.com">support@asteriscommerce.com</a> with the angle and deadline.
      </p>

      <h2>Built-in-public archive</h2>
      <p>
        Asteris ships in public — every Friday, what shipped that week is published. Once <a href="https://asterisforwoocommerce.com/blog" target="_blank" rel="noopener">/blog</a> on the WC site goes live (post-launch), it's the canonical archive of weekly drops. Until then, the <a href="https://asterisforwoocommerce.com/changelog" target="_blank" rel="noopener">changelog</a> + <a href="https://asterisforwoocommerce.com/roadmap" target="_blank" rel="noopener">roadmap</a> on the WC site are the public record.
      </p>

      <h2>Logos + brand assets</h2>
      <p>
        For high-resolution logos, the brand mark in SVG / PNG, screenshots, and approved colour palette: email <a href="mailto:support@asteriscommerce.com">support@asteriscommerce.com</a> with what you need and where it'll be used. We'll respond with a Dropbox / Drive link within one business day.
      </p>
      <p>
        Brand-palette quick reference (do not modify):
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Asteris Commerce (parent):</strong> ultraviolet <code>#AA00FF</code> on black</li>
        <li><strong>Asteris for WooCommerce:</strong> orange <code>#FF5B3F</code> on black</li>
        <li><strong>Asteris for WordPress:</strong> indigo <code>#3D5AFE</code> on black</li>
        <li><strong>Asteris Cart:</strong> green <code>#00C853</code> on black</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Review copies</h2>
      <p>
        Editors at WordPress trade publications (WP Mayor, WP Tavern, Torque, Post Status, Kinsta blog, GoDaddy Pro, similar). We provide review licences on request. Email <a href="mailto:support@asteriscommerce.com">support@asteriscommerce.com</a> with the publication name, your role, and which product you'd like to review.
      </p>
      <p>
        Independent reviewers / YouTubers / podcasters — please introduce yourself and the publication / channel. We'll respond within one business day.
      </p>

      <h2>Disclosure standards we follow</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>WordPress.org Trademark Guidelines — we never use "WordPress" or "WooCommerce" as a brand name; only descriptively (per Foundation guidelines).</li>
        <li>FTC / ACL disclosure — we never incentivise reviews, we never trade reviews for paid placement, and review licences are issued with the explicit understanding that there's no obligation to review favourably or at all.</li>
        <li>Affiliate disclosure — when we reference affiliated services (e.g. DataForSEO) in product copy, we disclose the affiliation on the relevant page.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>See also</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/about">About Asteris Commerce</a> — full company background</li>
        <li><a href="/roadmap">Cross-product roadmap</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://asterisforwoocommerce.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Asteris for WooCommerce</a> — the WC product site</li>
        <li><a href="https://asterisforwordpress.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Asteris for WordPress</a> — the WP product site</li>
        <li><a href="https://asteriscart.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Asteris Cart</a> — the focused checkout + funnel product site</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .hero {
    padding: 80px 0 40px;
  }
  h1 {
    font-size: 64px;
    line-height: 1;
    letter-spacing: -2px;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
  }
  .lead {
    font-size: 22px;
    color: var(--c-muted);
    max-width: 880px;
  }
  @media (max-width: 700px) { h1 { font-size: 40px; } }

  .stats {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(140px, 1fr));
    gap: 16px;
    margin-top: 40px;
    max-width: 880px;
  }
  .stat {
    background: var(--c-white);
    border: 2px solid var(--c-black);
    border-radius: var(--r-md);
    padding: 18px 14px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .stat-num {
    font-size: 28px;
    font-weight: 900;
    color: var(--c-violet, #AA00FF);
    line-height: 1;
    letter-spacing: -1px;
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }
  .stat-label {
    font-size: 14px;
    color: var(--c-muted);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .timeline {
    list-style: none;
    margin-left: 0;
    padding-left: 0;
  }
  .timeline li {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--c-violet, #AA00FF);
    padding: 0 0 6px 18px;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }
  .timeline li strong {
    display: inline-block;
    color: var(--c-violet, #AA00FF);
    margin-right: 8px;
    font-weight: 800;
  }

  .body { padding: 40px 0 80px; }
  .body h2 {
    font-size: 32px;
    margin: 40px 0 16px;
    color: var(--c-black);
  }
  .body p {
    font-size: 22px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: #333;
    margin-bottom: 18px;
  }
  .body p strong { color: var(--c-black); }
  .body p.quote {
    background: #f3eaff;
    border-left: 4px solid var(--c-violet, #AA00FF);
    padding: 18px 22px;
    font-size: 17px;
    color: var(--c-black);
    font-style: italic;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }
  .body ul {
    margin: 0 0 16px 24px;
    color: #333;
  }
  .body ul li {
    font-size: 22px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .body a { color: var(--c-orange); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 3px; }
  .body a:hover { color: var(--c-black); }
  .body code {
    background: #f5f5f5;
    padding: 2px 6px;
    border-radius: 3px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 16px;
  }
</style>
